  "prompt": "Why are sigma anti-bonding orbitals higher in energy than pi anti-bonding orbitals?",
  "response": "To understand why sigma anti-bonding orbitals are higher in energy than pi anti-bonding orbitals, we need to consider the molecular orbital theory and the characteristics of sigma and pi bonds. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. Orbital Overlap Mechanism:\n- Sigma (\u03c3) bonds form through head-on overlap of atomic orbitals\n- Pi (\u03c0) bonds form through side-by-side overlap of p orbitals\n\n2. Overlap Efficiency:\n- Sigma bonds have more direct, comprehensive orbital overlap\n- Pi bonds have less efficient, parallel orbital overlap\n\n3. Energy Considerations:\n- More direct overlap in sigma bonds results in:\n  a) Stronger bonding molecular orbitals\n  b) Higher energy anti-bonding molecular orbitals\n- Less efficient overlap in pi bonds leads to:\n  a) Weaker bonding molecular orbitals\n  b) Lower energy anti-bonding molecular orbitals\n\n4. Spatial Distribution:\n- Sigma anti-bonding orbitals have more nodes and less electron density\n- Pi anti-bonding orbitals have fewer nodes and more distributed electron density\n\nThese factors contribute to sigma anti-bonding orbitals being higher in energy compared to pi anti-bonding orbitals.",
